    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.29-32_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">29</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">THOMAS S. JONES, JR.
                        <lb/>
                    411 WEST 115TH STREET
                        <lb/>
                    NEW YORK CITY</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>September 27, 1929</dateline>
                
                    <note type="curatorial">[St Louis Post-Dispatch]</note>
                    <salute>My dear friend,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>A little over a week ago, I received from the publishers, an inscribed copy of William Pelley's <hi rend="underline">Golden Rabbish</hi>. The next day I had a letter from Putnam's, stating the you had suggested the book for me.</p>
                
                <p>Before writing Mr. Pelley, I want to get a word from you.*&#8212; I have read the book, and have enjoyed it greatly; though I have had conflicting feelings about it. &#8212; But, first to dispose of one point: all the 
                    <milestone unit="section"/>_____________________________________________________
                    <note type="authorial">*I have written the publishers of the receipt of the book.</note> 
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.29-32_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">30</fw>
                
                    'revelation' about Light being the <hi rend="underline">only reality</hi>; the Spectrum up to <unclear>White</unclear>; the carrying of the <unclear>life germ</unclear> <add>to the planet</add> by light; the halo; incarnated angels; the twelve disciples; the one on the earth: all this "came" to me ten years ago.&#8212; I was dumbfounded at the time (which has the period of your <hi rend="underline">Poet's <unclear>Town</unclear></hi> incident <add>&#8212; getting the line with the book turned down</add>), but I have learned to be more cautious as the years have gone by. &#8212;However, the extraordinary fact is that what is in his book is <hi rend="underline">exactly</hi> paralled to that "given" me immediately after the war.</p>
                    
                <p>This is the first point.&#8212; The second is my query
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.29-32_0003"/>
                    <fw type="authorial">2.</fw>
                    <fw type="curatorial">31</fw>
                                     
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">THOMAS S. JONES, JR.
                        <lb/>
                    411 WEST 115TH STREET
                        <lb/>
                    NEW YORK CITY</hi>
                </fw>
                    
                    on his title, which I think very unfortunate &#8212;as it will not draw readers, and his treatment of the story as a whole, and the <hi rend="underline">style</hi> itself &#8212; What do you think of those? &#8212; And what is the object of the book, and Mr. Pelley's own conviction? &#8212; Will you let me have a line on this?</p> 
                    
                    <milestone unit="section"/><ab>_____________</ab> 
                    
                <p>Daily I am hoping my Clipping Bureau will bring in your article on the Paterson book, for this 
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.29-32_0004"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">32</fw>
                    
                    will be a red-letter day for me. &#8212; By the way, my confirmation date of years ago comes Sunday &#8212; the Feast of <hi rend="caps">S.</hi> Michael. This has always been a day of great '<unclear>power</unclear>' with me. &#8212; Here is the sestet of a sonnet that came yesterday: (<hi rend="underline">Eve of the Guardian Angels</hi>)</p>
                    
                <lg>
                    <l>It breathes of worlds from whence the spirit came,</l>
                    <l>The vanished memory of a morning Star</l>
                    <l>Where dooms and shining destinies were spun.</l>
                    <l>Bend low and speak that long-forgotten Name,</l>
                    <l><unclear/> the Soul's Self and mighty avatar,</l>
                    <l>Great guardian angel, brighter than the sun!</l>
                </lg>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours</salute>
                    
                    <signed><unclear>TS Jones</unclear></signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
